      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Morgan_193158_1844_05_07_page01.jpg"/>
              <!--filenames for photos associated with this letter. Example: <pb n="1" facs="image1.jpg image2.jpg image3.jpg"/> -->
            <opener>
               <dateline><!--If there's no date line, omit this element. Record in the order in which it is written on the letter.-->
                  <name type="place" ref="./Placeography.xml#Edgeworthstown_IE"/>Edgeworths Town
                  <date when="1844-05-07"/>May 7<hi rend="superscript">h.</hi> 1844. </dateline>
               <salute>
                  <persName>My dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HughX1">M<hi rend="superscript">[superscript]rs[/superscript]</hi>. Hughes</persName>
                     <!-- Use if letter has a saluation ("Dear Sir," for example). If not, delete this line.-->
                  </persName>
               </salute>
            </opener>
            <p>Your letter followed me to<lb/>
               my home here which I have<lb/>
               reached but a few days ago &amp;<lb/>
               I take the earliest moment <lb/>
               I can from talking and<lb/>
               listening to <hi rend="underline">at home and</hi><lb/>
               <hi rend="underline">abroad</hi> anecdotes to than<lb/>k
               you for the Grace which you<lb/>
               have been so kind as to make<lb/>
               out for me - It is curious that <lb/>
               in my way home on a visit I<lb/>
               paid to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HollaH1">D<hi rend="superscript">r.</hi> Hollands</persName> family<lb/>
               I happening to mention my<lb/>
               want of this grace &amp; all the <choice><orig>enqui<lb/>
                  ries</orig><reg>enquiries</reg></choice> I had made for it <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HollX1">Miss <choice><orig>Hol<lb/>
                     land</orig><reg>Holland</reg></choice></persName> recollected that she had <lb/>
               seen it in one of the little books<lb/>
               in her village school and she<lb/>
               pick it for me - Her version<lb/>
               <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Morgan_193158_1844_05_07_page02.jpg"/>
               I do not think so good or so real<lb/>
               as yours - Here it is <lb/>
            </p>
            <p>Some have meal &amp; cannot eat it<lb/>
               Some have none &amp; fain w<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> get it <lb/>
               We have meal &amp; we can eat it<lb/>
               The Lord be thanked for it<lb/>
               </p>
            <p>There is a great want of <lb/>
               The teeth and the antithesis<lb/>
               in this grace - I prefer the teeth<lb/>
               to eat - and even the <hi rend="underline">rhyme</hi><lb/>
               to the ear not the eye in<lb/>
               want-it<lb/>
               &amp; <hi rend="underline">thank-ed</hi><lb/>
               often pronounced thank <hi rend="underline">ed</hi><lb/>
                         
            </p>
            <p>My mind is now quite satisfied<lb/>
               teaching this grace - and much<lb/>
               amused we were with your <lb/>
               schoolmaster's <add>three pence</add> extra charge for<lb/>
               teaching <hi rend="underline">the graces</hi><lb/>
            </p>
            <p>You will be glad to hear that<lb/>
               I found all well &amp; happy at my<lb/> 
               home &amp; that I am well &amp; happy<lb/>
               myself and much the happier for <lb/>
               <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Morgan_193158_1844_05_07_page03.jpg"/>
               having <del>left and</del> found <persName>my sister</persName><!--which sister is this?--><lb/>
               so well all he time I was with<lb/>
               her this winter &amp; spring - a most<lb/>
               happy time it was! meeting with<lb/>
               so many kind friends of long<lb/>
               standing unchanged - yourself<lb/>
               among the number -</p>
            <p><persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF2">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Edgeworth</persName> sets out this week<lb/>
               for <placeName ref="./Placeography.xmlLondon_ENK">London</placeName> and will be <choice><orig>con<lb/>
                  vyed</orig><reg>convyed</reg></choice> to N<hi rend="superscript">p</hi>. <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#1-North-Audley-Street_ENK">1 North Audley St</placeName>.<lb/> 
               by her son <persName>Pakenham</persName><!--Michael Pakenham, no ID in Taxonomy sheet-->; they will<lb/>
               I hope spend a happy summer<lb/>
               together with <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">Fanny</persName> &amp; <persName ref="./Personography.xml#WilsL2">Lestock<lb/>
                  Wilson</persName> - <lb/></p>
            <p>Adieu my dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HughX1">M<hi rend="superscript">[superscript]rs.[/superscript]</hi> Hughes</persName><lb/>
               Pray remember me kindly <lb/>
               to your son &amp; believe me<lb/> </p>
            
            <closer>Your obliged &amp; affectionate<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria Edgeworth</persName><lb/>
               <!--include linebreaks, if used. example: <closer> Yours<lb/> Very sincerely<lb/> -->
            </closer>
            <postscript>
               <p><!--A postscript goes here, outside the <closer>. --></p>
            </postscript>
            <!--You can include a <pb/> here, or inside the postScript.-->
